4 (g) Temporary Absence. – An otherwise qualifying owner does not lose the benefit of
5 this circuit breaker because of a temporary absence from his or her permanent residence for
6 reasons of health, or because of an extended absence while confined to a rest home or nursing
7 home, so long as the residence is unoccupied or occupied by the owner's spouse or other
8 dependent.
9 (h) Deferred Taxes. – The difference between the taxes due under this section and the
10 taxes that would have been payable in the absence of this section are a lien on the real property
11 of the taxpayer as provided in G.S. 105-355(a). G.S. 105-355(a); provided, however, liens
12 remaining after (i) a qualifying owner's death or (ii) the devise of the property to a member of
13 the owner's family, as defined in subdivision (i)(1) of this section, shall be deemed satisfied and
14 no deferred taxes shall be due thereon. The difference in taxes must be carried forward in the
15 records of each taxing unit as deferred taxes. The deferred taxes for the preceding three fiscal
16 years are due and payable in accordance with G.S. 105-277.1F when the property loses its
17 eligibility for deferral as a result of a disqualifying event described in subsection (i) of this
18 section. On or before September 1 of each year, the collector must send to the mailing address of
19 a residence on which taxes have been deferred a notice stating the amount of deferred taxes and
20 interest that would be due and payable upon the occurrence of a disqualifying event.
21 (i) Disqualifying Events. – Each of the following constitutes a disqualifying event:
22 (1) The owner transfers the residence. Transfer of the residence is not a
23 disqualifying event if (i) the owner transfers the residence to a co-owner of
24 the residence or, as part of a divorce proceeding, to his or her spouse and (ii)
25 that individual occupies or continues to occupy the property as his or her
26 permanent residence.residence or (ii) the owner transfers the residence to a
27 member of the owner's family and the person to whom the residence was
28 transferred satisfies the income eligibility limit provided by this section. For
29 purposes of this subdivision, "family" means the owner's, or the owner's
30 spouse's lineal descendant, lineal ascendant, or sibling, and the spouse of any
31 of these individuals.
32 (2) The owner dies. Death of the owner is not a disqualifying event if (i) the
33 owner's share passes to a co-owner of the residence or to his or her spouse and
34 (ii) that individual occupies or continues to occupy the property as his or her
35 permanent residence.
36 (3) The owner ceases to use the property as a permanent residence.
37 …."
