6 shall be exempted from taxation if: (i) As to real property, it is actually and exclusively occupied
7 and used, and as to personal property, it is entirely and completely used, by the owner for
8 charitable purposes; and (ii) the owner is not organized or operated for profit.
9 (b) A charitable purpose within the meaning of this section is one that has humane and
10 philanthropic objectives; it is an activity that benefits humanity or a significant rather than limited
11 segment of the community without expectation of pecuniary profit or reward. The humane
12 treatment of animals is also a charitable purpose.
13 (c) The fact that a building or facility is incidentally available to and patronized by the
14 general public, so long as there is no material amount of business or patronage with the general
15 public, shall does not defeat the exemption granted by this section.
16 (d) Notwithstanding the exclusive-use exclusive use requirements of this section, if part
17 of a property that otherwise meets the section's requirements is used for a purpose that would
18 require exemption under subsection (a), above, if the entire property were so used, the valuation
19 of the part so used shall be exempted is exempt from taxation.
20 (e) Real property held by an organization described in subdivision (a)(8) for a charitable
21 purpose under this section as a future site for housing housing, other than affordable rental
22 housing as defined in G.S. 105-278.7A, for individuals or families with low or moderate incomes
23 may be classified under this section for no more than 10 five years. The taxes that would
24 otherwise be due on real property exempt under this subsection shall be are a lien on the property
25 as provided in G.S. 105-355(a). The taxes shall be are carried forward in the records of the taxing
26 unit as deferred taxes. The deferred taxes are due and payable in accordance with
27 G.S. 105-277.1F when the property loses its eligibility for deferral as a result of a disqualifying
28 event. A disqualifying event occurs when the property was is not used for low- or
29 moderate-income housing within 10 five years from the first day of the fiscal year the property
30 was classified under this subsection. In addition to the provisions in G.S. 105-277.1F, all liens
31 arising under this subdivision are extinguished when the property is used for low- or
32 moderate-income housing within the time period allowed under this subsection."
33 SECTION 3.(b) Article 12 of Chapter 105 of the General Statutes is amended by
34 adding the following new section to read:
35 "§ 105-278.7A. Real and personal property owned, in whole or in part, by a charitable
36 nonprofit and used for affordable rental housing.
37 (a) Exemption Generally. – Real and personal property owned by an eligible owner and
38 used for a charitable purpose in the operation of affordable rental housing is exempt from taxation
39 to the extent provided in this section if the requirements of this section are met.
40 (b) Definitions. –The following definitions apply in this section:
41 (1) Affiliate. – Defined in G.S. 105-130.2.
42 (2) Affordable rental housing. – A rental housing development consisting of land
43 and improvements in which more than fifty percent (50%) of the units are
44 qualifying units.
45 (3) Charitable purpose. – A charitable purpose within the meaning of this section
46 is one that has humane and philanthropic objectives; it is an activity that
47 benefits humanity or a significant rather than limited segment of the
48 community without expectation of pecuniary profit or reward.
49 (4) Eligible joint venture. – A limited partnership, limited liability company, or
50 limited liability partnership in which a general partner or limited liability
51 company managing member is an eligible nonprofit corporation.
Page 4 House Bill 1092-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) Eligible nonprofit corporation. – A nonprofit described in 501(c)(3) of the
2 Code that (i) is exempt from federal income taxation under section 501(a) of
3 the Code, (ii) is incorporated under a certificate of existence or admitted under
4 a certificate of authority under the North Carolina Nonprofit Corporation Act
5 as provided in Chapter 55A of the General Statutes, and (iii) has day-to-day
6 control of the operations of and decisions for the affordable rental housing and
7 has not delegated any decision-making authority other than to a property
8 manager serving under the direction of the eligible owner. The term includes
9 a single-purpose entity wholly owned by an eligible nonprofit corporation.
10 (6) Eligible owner. – An eligible joint venture or an eligible nonprofit corporation.
11 (7) Income limit. – Eighty percent (80%) of area median income, adjusted for
12 family size, as set and most recently published by the U.S. Department of
13 Housing and Urban Development.
14 (8) Qualifying unit. – An affordable rental housing unit for which both of the
15 following conditions are met:
16 a. The rent charged for an occupied unit or the published rent for a vacant
17 unit is at or below the rent limit.
18 b. It is occupied by, or set aside for, a tenant whose income is at or below
19 the income limit.
20 (9) Rent limit. – Rent, plus a utility allowance calculated in accordance with the
21 requirements of the North Carolina Housing Finance Agency, that does not
22 exceed thirty percent (30%) of the income limit.
23 (c) Requirements for Government-Supported Affordable Rental Housing. – Real and
24 personal property that provides government-supported affordable rental housing is exempt from
25 property taxation in any year in which all of the conditions listed in this subsection are met. For
26 purposes of this subsection, the term "government-supported" means that the property is financed
27 as described in sub-subdivision a. or b. of subdivision (2) of this subsection. The conditions are:
28 (1) The property is owned and operated by an eligible nonprofit corporation or an
29 eligible joint venture.
30 (2) Either of the following applies:
31 a. The eligible owner is an eligible joint venture that receives
32 low-income housing credits pursuant to section 42 of the Code and
33 that is in compliance with any applicable regulatory requirements as
34 determined by the North Carolina Housing Finance Agency.
35 Ownership is determined as of the date the certificate of occupancy is
36 issued.
37 b. The eligible owner finances the acquisition, rehabilitation,
38 development, or operation of the property, or any combination thereof,
39 with tax-exempt mortgage revenue bonds, qualified 501(c)(3) bonds,
40 federal direct loans or grants, State loans or grants, or loans or grants
41 provided by a local jurisdiction in which the property is located. Such
42 government support must require the execution of a deed restriction or
43 enforceable, verifiable agreement with a public agency requiring that
44 the property be operated as affordable rental housing in accordance
45 with this section for a period of at least 15 years from the date the
46 financing or financial assistance was initially provided. Government
47 support does not include payments made to the owner under the federal
48 Housing Choice Voucher Program or other local, State, or federal
49 voucher program.
50 (d) Requirements for Non-Government-Supported Affordable Rental Housing. – Real
51 and personal property that provides non-government-supported affordable rental housing is
