General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 exempt from property taxation in any year in which all of the conditions listed in this subsection
2 are met. For purposes of this subsection, the term "non-government-supported" means that the
3 property is not financed as described in sub-subdivision a. or b. of subdivision (2) of subsection
4 (c) of this section. The conditions are:
5 (1) The property is one hundred percent (100%) owned and operated by an
6 eligible nonprofit corporation that has owned and operated affordable rental
7 housing for at least five years.
8 (2) The eligible nonprofit corporation, including any of its subsidiaries or
9 nonprofit affiliates, does not receive any funding or financial assistance, other
10 than grants, from a for-profit affiliate.
11 (3) The eligible nonprofit corporation does not lease the affordable rental housing
12 land or improvements to another entity. This subdivision does not apply to the
13 leasing of affordable rental housing units to tenants.
14 (4) The eligible nonprofit corporation has executed a deed restriction in favor of
15 the county and any municipality in which the property is located requiring that
16 the property be operated as affordable rental housing in accordance with this
17 section for a period of at least 15 years from the date of application. The
18 restriction must require that the owner provide the reporting required under
19 subsection (g) of this section annually to all grantees for the term of the deed
20 restriction. The deed restriction must state that any grantee, or its assigns, has
21 the right to enforce the terms of the restriction.
22 (e) Exemption Amount. – The exemption amount is the percentage of the appraised value
23 that is equal to the percentage of qualifying units unless the eligible owner meets the requirements
24 of the safe harbor in Section 3 of Internal Revenue Service Rev. Proc. 96-32, in which case the
25 exemption amount is one hundred percent (100%) of the appraised value of the property. A
26 transition period of one taxable year applies to improved and occupied rental housing property
27 purchased by an eligible owner for which the eligible owner cannot provide the total household
28 income for each qualifying unit at the time of application but that otherwise meets the
29 requirements of this section. During the transition period, a "qualifying unit" is an affordable
30 rental housing unit for which the rent charged is at or below the rent limit for purposes of
31 determining the exemption amount.
32 (f) Application. – To be eligible for an exemption under this section, an eligible owner
33 must submit an application in accordance with G.S. 105-282.1. The application form shall
34 require the applicant to provide the following information:
35 (1) Whether the applicant is applying for the exemption under subsection (c) or
36 subsection (d) of this section, along with documentation supporting that the
37 applicant is an eligible owner for the subsection under which it is applying;
38 evidence of government support pursuant to sub-subdivision a. or b. of
39 subdivision (2) of subsection (c) of this section, if applicable; and a copy of
40 the applicable deed restriction or regulatory agreement.
41 (2) Whether the property is subject to a transition period as described in
42 subsection (e) of this section.
43 (3) Either of the following, as of last day of the month immediately preceding
44 January 1 of the year of application:
45 a. If the applicant is applying for an exemption amount based on the
46 percentage of qualifying units, the percentage of qualifying units by
47 providing the following items:
48 1. The rent amount received by the owner for each qualifying unit
49 as evidenced by an anonymized rent roll. The applicant must
50 provide evidence of the published rent if a unit is vacant.
