12 NCACC GRANT FUNDING FOR REAPPRAISAL TECHNOLOGY
13 SECTION 4.(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the North Carolina
14 Association of County Commissioners (Association) the nonrecurring sum of twenty million
15 dollars ($20,000,000) for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be used by the Association to provide
16 grants to local governments for the purpose of transitioning those governments to shortened
17 reappraisal cycles and thereby ensure more frequent and accurate property valuations. Grant
18 funds provided under this section shall be used by local governments for (i) technical assistance
19 and (ii) one-time capital investments in technological infrastructure that improve local capacity
20 and efficiency in conducting reappraisals, including the acquisition of specialized software, data
21 migration, and the implementation of digital systems. In awarding grants under this section, the
22 Association shall prioritize awarding grants to local governments operating on a reappraisal cycle
23 of more than four years. For purposes of this section, "local governments" means counties, cities,
24 or towns conducting reappraisals of property under Subchapter II of Chapter 105 of the General
25 Statutes as of the effective date of this section.
26 SECTION 4.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2026.
27
28 EFFECTIVE DATE
29 SECTION 5. Section 2 of this act becomes effective for taxable years beginning on
30 or after July 1, 2027, only if the constitutional amendment proposed by Section 1 of this act is
31 approved; otherwise, Section 2 of this act shall have no effect. Unless otherwise provided, the
32 remainder of this act is effective when it becomes law.
